Finally this issue can be put to rest.  Pets have been breaking mez ever since the new mez code went in.  It was a lot less than before, but it was still happening.  Strange though since the conditions when it happens can't really be defined (or at least I can't see a pattern).  It has nothing to do with casting, and I doubt it has to do with melee timing.  I think it's more about hate lists or who hit who first or something.  Might be zone related too (VL was really bad, PoV seems not so bad).<br>
<br>
Anyway, Pets do (and have been) breaking mez.  Just now there's no way to deny it.<br>
<br>
As for DoT's, yes the person who cast the DoT is shown as breaking mez.  I did this to myself - cast Mez, thought I was singing mana song, but hit my slow DoT, and it kept saying I was breaking Mez, which was ticking me off until I saw what I was doing (fingers off by one hot-key).  Heh.<br>
<br>
Anyway, this is great code and a great message.  Being a regular mezzer, I like to call people Dork who break mez early.  It makes me laugh (yes I'm odd).  So far it seems that Rogue's like to break mez early, especially with a Pally (who stuns first, but the stun doesn't actually break the mez).<br>
