<br>
Now, I've spent quite a bit of time as a programmer for multi-user databases.  Atomic locking is easy, but it's also quite easy to get into race conditions that cause two processes to lock and update the same section of memory at the same time.  Not supposed to happen, but it does, all the same.<br>
<br>
One of the issues that I've found in the past is that the same code that sets locks is usually also used to report locks.  If you have a bug in the one, you typically have a bug in the other as well.<br>
<br>
Bringing this back to EQ, I'd be surprised if the same code that's used to detect if mez is broken isn't also used in reporting if mez is active, as well as reporting who broke mez.  Since we know for a fact that there's problems in this area, I question whether or not the code reporting who broke mez works in all cases as well.<br>
<br>
Note that you can't just say, &quot;Seems to work fine&quot;, since you have no way at all to tell who broke mez, except the code that returns it to you.<br>
<br>
That's my point.  Done with this now :-) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kathartic>Kathartic</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 19<br> <font color=#333333>(1/31/03 9:22:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=973.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   code works well?</span><hr size=1> I have to say, after doing a crawl with an enchanter in group, that this is not all that reliable.  We had a lot of mezzed mobs and sometimes there was no indication of who broke the mez despite the fact that someone broke the mez.  We had no inappropriate mez breaks since it was a well oiled guild group however there were many occasions when there was no message and other times that there were.  If a few occurances I could believe that the mez just dropped while taunt was occuring.  I do know this group well and have extensive grouping experience with this particular MA from both the mage point of view as well as from my enchanter's point of view.  He does not wait for mez to drop in most cases.  He typically does two casts of his taunt spell the breaks mez.<br>
<br>
I will do a little more careful watching as well as discussion to confirm however at this time I'd consider the code about as reliable as most new features (and many old ones) that has been implemented.<br>
<br>
Anyone else notice this lack of reliability?<br>
